{"meta":{"domain":"subjects","kid":"5357","authors":[{"fullname":"Nicolas Tournadre","id":"6"}],"title":"","dates":{"created_at":"2013-09-15 04:15:58 UTC","updated_at":"2013-09-15 04:15:58 UTC"}},"nodes":[{"index":0,"parent_index":-1,"body":"<p class=\"Paragraph\">If it happens that the source of a quotation is the same person as someone who is mentioned in it, or else is the actual speaker, Tibetans prefer to substitute \u201chybrid\u201d reported speech for direct speech. For example, in the statement \u201cHe said \u2018I\u2019m a doctor,\u2019\u201d the two pronouns \u201che\u201d and \u201cI\u201d refer to the same person (and are therefore \u201ccoreferents\u201d). The same is true of the statement \u201cHe said to me, \u2018You\u2019re not a doctor!\u2019\u201d in which the pronouns \u201cme\u201d and \u201cyou\u201d are coreferents. In such cases, Tibetan generally uses a particular form of reported speech that has the following features:<\/p><p class=\"Paragraph\">A. The pronouns of the original quotation and the register (honorific, humilific, or ordinary) are <strong>reformulated <\/strong>to suit the speaker\u2019s current situation. This is similar to the reported speech of European languages.<\/p><p class=\"Paragraph\">B. By contrast, when the first person pronoun \u201cI,\u201d \u201cme,\u201d etc. appears in the original citation, the <strong>egophoric <\/strong>auxiliary (<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f61\u0f72\u0f53\u0f0b<\/span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f56\u0fb1\u0f74\u0f44\u0f0b<\/span>, etc.) that is associated with it is preserved in the \u201chybrid\u201d reported speech.<\/p><p class=\"Paragraph\">C. Once a sentence has been transformed into reported speech, if it contains coreferential nouns or pronouns one of the two forms is <strong>dropped<\/strong>.<\/p><table border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"> <tbody> <tr> <td width=\"390\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\" style=\"text-align: center;\">\u201cQuotation + Auxiliary (egophoric)\u201d + <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f5f\u0f7a\u0f0b<\/span> + Verb of speech<\/p> <\/td> <\/tr> <\/tbody> <\/table><p class=\"Paragraph\">For example, the sentence \u201cHe said, \u2018I\u2019m a doctor\u2019\u201d is transformed into the hypothetical stage A): *<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f41\u0f7c\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f42\u0f72\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f41\u0f7c\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f68\u0f7a\u0f58\u0f0b\u0f46\u0f72\u0f0b\u0f61\u0f72\u0f53\u0f0b\u0f5f\u0f7a\u0f0b\u0f63\u0f56\u0f0b\u0f66\u0f7c\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f0d<\/span>. Following the rule set out in B), the sentence preserves the egophoric auxiliary <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f61\u0f72\u0f53\u0f0b<\/span>; and as a result of eliminating the first pronoun, we end up with: <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f41\u0f7c\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f68\u0f7a\u0f58\u0f0b\u0f46\u0f72\u0f0b\u0f61\u0f72\u0f53\u0f0b\u0f5f\u0f7a\u0f0b\u0f63\u0f56\u0f0b\u0f66\u0f7c\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f0d<\/span> \u201cHe said he was a doctor.\u201d<\/p><p class=\"Paragraph\">Here are some other examples of indirect reported speech:<\/p><ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f41\u0f7c\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f42\u0f72\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f68\u0f7a\u0f58\u0f0b\u0f46\u0f72\u0f0b\u0f58\u0f0b\u0f62\u0f7a\u0f51\u0f0b\u0f5f\u0f7a\u0f0b\u0f66\u0f74\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f56\u0fb1\u0f74\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f0d<\/span> \u201cHe told me I wasn\u2019t a doctor.\u201d<\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f51\u0f7c\u0f53\u0f0b\u0f42\u0fb2\u0f74\u0f56\u0f0b\u0f40\u0fb1\u0f72\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f61\u0f72\u0f0b\u0f42\u0f7a\u0f0b\u0f60\u0f56\u0fb1\u0f7c\u0f62\u0f0b\u0f58\u0f0b\u0f60\u0f56\u0fb1\u0f74\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f5f\u0f7a\u0f0b\u0f63\u0f56\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f0b\u0f62\u0f7a\u0f51\u0f0d<\/span> \u201cD\u00f6ndrup said he hadn\u2019t received a letter.\u201d (In this case, the subject could also be in the dative.)<\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f62\u0f92\u0f53\u0f0b\u0f63\u0f42\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f63\u0f58\u0f0b\u0f66\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f5a\u0f74\u0f62\u0f0b\u0f55\u0f7a\u0f56\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f42\u0f72\u0f0b\u0f61\u0f72\u0f53\u0f0b\u0f5f\u0f7a\u0f0b\u0f42\u0f66\u0f74\u0f44\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f66\u0f7c\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f0d<\/span> \u201cThe teacher said he would come back immediately.\u201d<\/li> <\/ul><ul> <li> <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f5a\u0f7a\u0f0b\u0f62\u0f72\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f42\u0f72\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f61\u0f72\u0f0b\u0f42\u0f7a\u0f0b\u0f42\u0f4f\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f0b\u0f61\u0f72\u0f53\u0f0b\u0f5f\u0f7a\u0f0b\u0f63\u0f53\u0f0b\u0f56\u0f62\u0f92\u0fb1\u0f56\u0f0b\u0f66\u0f7c\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f0d<\/span> \u201cTsering replied that he\u2019d sent the letter.\u201d<\/li> <\/ul>","title":""}]}
